$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
        Introduce equality axioms ax-9v and ax-12
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

  ${
    $d x y $.
    $( Axiom B8 of [Tarski] p. 75, which is the same as our axiom ~ ax-9
       weakened with a distinct variable condition.  Theorem ~ ax9 shows the
       derivation of ~ ax-9 from this one.  (Contributed by NM, 7-Nov-2015.) $)
    ax-9v $a |- -. A. x -. x = y $.
  $}

  $( Axiom of Quantifier Introduction.  One of the equality and substitution
     axioms of predicate calculus with equality.

     The antecedents imply ` -. x = z ` as well as ` -. x = y ` , so ` x ` must
     be a different variable from both ` y ` and ` z ` if the antecedents
     hold.  The axiom essentially states that if ` x ` is neither ` y ` nor
     ` z ` , then it is irrelevant to the truth of ` y = z ` .

     The original version of this axiom was ~ ax-12o ("o" for "old") and was
     replaced with this shorter ~ ax-12 in December 2015.  The old axiom is
     proved from this one as theorem ~ ax12o .  Conversely, this axiom is
     proved from ~ ax-12o as theorem ~ ax12 .

     Although this version is shorter, the original version ~ ax-12o may be
     more intuitive to understand, as well as more practical to work with,
     because of the "distinctor" form of its antecedents.

     This axiom can be weakened if desired by adding distinct variable
     restrictions on pairs ` x , z ` and ` y , z ` , and from it we can still
     derive the original ~ ax-12o since we will still satisfy the hypotheses of
     ~ ax12olem24 .  (This may be useful for reducing variable "bundling" in
     some applications.  We conjecture that variables ` x ` and ` y ` must be
     bundled, though, for the full strength of the axiom i.e. for metalogical
     completeness of the system.)  (Contributed by NM, 21-Dec-2015.) $)
  ax-12 $a |- ( -. x = y -> ( y = z -> A. x y = z ) ) $.

